column168: The shipment was tendered to FLL as general cargo. Upon loading of the cargo the crate nd departed to EWR. The supervisor at FLL recived a Load Discrepancy Message later that evening and started to investigate what was loaded on the flight.  The supervosr of FLL called the shipper and determined it was a generator that contained oil as posssible UN3363. Upon arrival at EWR it was notice the cargo had fallen over and oil spilled on the floor of Pit2. The maintainace team at EWR cleaned up the spill. The cargo was loaded onto a flight to AMS. The AWB and crate has no infomation listed or marks showing it was Hazardous Materials.

column168: On December 06, 2013, at an R&L Carriers terminal a 275 gallon tote of UN1263 Combustible Liquid Paint Primer experienced an apparent puncture of the internal bladder of the tote. It was reported that no visible damage was seen to the exterior section of the tote. It was reported that an estimated less than 5 gallons of the material impacted a 10' x 6' are of the interior of the trailer as well as a metal containment pan that the damaged tote was placed into by facility personnel. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one and staged onsite. The damaged tote was wrapped with absorbent pads and shrink wrap to keep any residual materials from releasing. The damaged tote was then staged onsite to be sent back to the shipper. Granular absorbents were worked in thoroughly into the impacted trailer and then containerized. Absorbent pads were used to clean the metal containment pan. All impacted absorbents and debris were containerized and transported offsite for pending disposal.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the ten day storage dock of the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon opening the door, it was noticed that there was liquid all over the floor of the trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found that a lid on a drum had popped off.  The spilled liquid was cleaned up with a suitable absorbant material and the drum was placed into an overpack container along with the absorbents used to clean the trailer floor.  A small amount dripped onto the containment area where the trailer was parked.  The drum was then accepted into the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The trailer was loaded by the generator.  The driver felt that the forklift operator may have hit the drum with another drum and popped the lid off, but he did not see anything leaking when he left the generator.  The generator was notified of the incident to handle with their dock personnel.

On December 03, 2013, a Dupre Logistics 406 cargo tanker was offloading diesel fuel into an AST when the hose separated from the fitting resulting in the release of an estimated 27 gallons of diesel fuel onto the soil/gravel/concrete ground. The impacted area was estimated at 20' x 30'. The estimated amount released was determined by using the tank manufactures strapping chart. No drains or waterways had been impacted by the release.  The contractor scraped the area containerized all impacted soil and gravel. The area was then sprayed with biomatrix and the contractor departed the site.  On December 04, 2013, the contractor arrived back onsite to prepare a cost estimated for a needed excavation.  On December 13, 2013, the contractor excavated the impacted area. A clearance sample along with a background sample was taken. The area was then back filled and restored back to its original condition. All waste was containerized and transported offsite for pending disposal.

column168: At approximately 4:15 PM on Tuesday November 10, 2013 it was reported that tank car TILX 101295 was "wet" and appeared to be leaking from the top of the car. Mechanical personnel notified the trainmaster who then made the appropriate notifications. The car was isolated, a buffer zone established for safety, and emergency responders activated.    Once on site responders conducted a safety briefing and then accessed the railcar. All tank car appurtenances were inspected for tightness and upon further inspection it was determined that the fill hole cover was improperly tightened during loading, creating a small gap for product to escape on one side. The fill hole gasket was verified compatible and in good repair and responders re-tightened fill hole cover in appropriate order. Once tightened, a slosh test was performed on the car. No new leaks detected. Lading that had leaked was neutralized and wiped from the top and sides of the railcar. Once tank car was decontaminated adequately, it was released for normal transportation.    * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.      (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: At approximately 11:32 PM on 12/3/2013 KCSR train crew set out a cut of cars on the Beaumont sub MP 625.8 and reported a strong odor coming from the empty car GATX 201258 last contained (Anhydrous Ammonia). Appropriate notifications were made and hazmat responders activated.     *No injuries reported    At approximately 3:00 AM on 12/4/13 (the following morning) responders arrived on site, met with KCSR representative to discuss safety briefing and locate the car. Once the site was deemed safe, responders accessed the tank car. Upon further inspection of the car, it was noted that the release point was coming from the O-Ring cap of the Pressure Relief Device (PRD). Incorrect/incompatible o-ring in PRD. Responders removed o-rings, cleaned, and replaced "flipped around," the o-rings into the PRD. After several air monitoring events, it was noted that the leak had stopped and the field repair was deemed adequate for the package to continue to final destination.     The tank car was secured and responders demobilized from location    File Note: Item 13-The consignee address and final destination are different according to the waybill. The consignee's information was populated on item #13, the final destination address is as follows:    MARTIN PRODUCT SALES LLC  1 GULF STATES RD  BEAUMONT, TX 77725      File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. column168: A flatbed trailer containing 2 large transformers on a secondary containment pan was in route from the pickup point to the intended waste disposal facility. About 5 miles north of the facility on US Hwy 169, the driver had to apply his brakes very hard to avoid a collision and the load shifted.  The driver inspected the load and noticed a small drip from one of the transformers.  Apparently one of the radiator fins was breached when the rear transformer slid into the front transformer and PCB oil began to leak.  As the truck continued to the in the intended waste treatment facility located in Coffeyville some PCB oil was lost.  When the load arrived at the waste treatment facility there was leaked PCB oil both in the pan and on the trailer. A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and worked through the night cleaning the oil trail on the highway from the location where the incident occurred to the disposal facility.  The sheriff's department and local fire department was notified and came to the scene to monitor the cleanup activities.  The KDHE (Mr. John Jones) was notified, incident # 35001; EPA (Mr. John Frey) was notified; and, the NRC (Officer Hardy) was notified, incident # 1067360. The total volume lost from the transformer was estimated to be 28 gallons.  Of the total volume lost, 8 gallons was contained in the spill pan and the remaining 20 gallons was released.  Of the 20 gallons released, 10 gallons was released to the highway access with 5 gallons of the 10 gallons spilled in a localized area approximately 100 yards north of where the railroad crosses the highway.  The localized release was excavated, removed, sampled and backfilled.  The remaining 10 gallons was released on the waste management facility property.  Discernible release points on the Hwy. were hexane rinsed, absorbed with oil absorbent, then the absorbent was removed.  The concentration of the released PCB liquid was 760,000 ppm.
column169: The driver was suspended for 10 days, was re-trained on load securement, accident/incident reporting and on-road contingency plan.  In addition, the dispatcher received a written warning and retraining on incident reporting/spill plan.  Both individuals will present a lessons learned to the entire staff at an upcoming safety meeting.  As far as the cleanup goes the activities continue.  See Part 6 of this form regarding all corrective actions completed to date.  The company will be approaching EPA to determine if any additional cleanup will be required.

column168: On December 12, 2013, at an R&L Carriers facility a shipment of UN2014 Hydrogen Peroxide drums arrived at the terminal with 4 of the drums having small amounts of the material on the lids. An estimated 3-4 ounces total between all four drums. A contractor arrived onsite and pH tested the liquid and determined it was indeed the product. The tops were wiped down and neutralized. The bung hole caps were then tightened down as well. The rags used to handle the cleanup were then transported offsite to be combined with like waste at the contractors facility.

This incident occurred at DHL Express USA, 236 Wendell H Ford Blvd, Erlanger, KY 41018. US Customs contacted the DHL Emergency Spill Responders on 12/3/2013 to report a shipment held in their area that needed attention. The shipment had been x-rayed and had raised the suspicions of Customs Agent Lance Love. The Customs Agents opened the shipment, inspected the contents and found two sets of small connected lithium ion batteries. They decided to cut through one of the batteries to inspect the contents. Subsequently, the Emergency Responders were called to the area to provide clean up and dispose of the damaged lithium ion battery. This shipment was not marked or labeled as containing lithium batteries. Transport via air was confirmed.

The damaged drum released approximately 3 gallons of material to the interior of the trailer.  No areas outside of the trailer were impacted by the release. At 0824 EST R&L Carriers contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS).  ERTS then contacted Hull's Environmental, an environmental contractor.  Hull's personnel arrived on-site, overpacked the damaged drum, applied absorbents to the released material, and worked them in thoroughly.  The impacted absorbents were then containerized for disposal.

column168: At 0930 EST, Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) was notified about the punctured tote. HazChem personnel wiped the damaged tote with absorbents pads, and applied absorbent materials to the released material on the ground. column168: A Quality Carriers driver was turning into a truck stop when he observed UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid leaking from a loose primary valve flange to the tank flange.The repair to the loose flange was repaired on site. The driver stopped the unit and the local hazmat team responded to secure the release and a second unit was dispatched to transfer the material. It was originally reported that up to 30 gallons of material was released onto the asphalt parking area. Upon arrival of a response contractor it was discovered that approximately 500 gallons of material had been released prior to the transfer being completed. The material impacted an approximate 60'x500' area of the parking area and had entered a storm drain which leads to a dry retention basin. Neutralizing agent was applied to the drains then flushed into the retention basin resulting in impact to a 60'x80' area of soil to be impacted.

column168: A Clean Harbor's driver pulling a 6000 gallon tanker arrived at his disposal facility, upon walk around inspection driver noticed that a small amount of material had leaked from the top of tankers manway.The 4 inch port cap had become dislodged and was lying in the manway compartment. The driver then contacted his home dispatcher and a local response team donning the proper personal protective  equipment cleaned the leaked material from the tanker. The port cap was secured; the tanker was emptied and returned to service.
column169: While it is believed that the port cap was installed and locked, the driver did not check, and the cap should have had a secondary locking strap or method.  Driver  disciplined for stating that he verified securement when in fact he did not.  Dispatcher and managers reviewed this incident with all drivers and put in place a procedure to ensure that all such port caps are secured by secondary means i.e. zip ties or tape.

column168: On 12-4-2013 at approximately 8:45 AM, a Roche Carolina Inc. (RCI) utilities operator observed material overflowing from the top of a Clean Harbors tanker truck.  Organic waste from an RCI hazardous waste storage tank was being loaded to the tanker truck.  The utilities operator contacted the tank farm control room and instructed the tank farm operator to shut off the transfer pump.  The tank farm operator shutdown the pump and responded to the tank truck.  Site Emergency Response personnel were immediately notified of the incident.  The material that overflowed the tanker truck was fully contained in an epoxy-lined, concrete containment sump.  Based on observations from material handling personnel, it is estimated that 100 gallons of hazardous organic waste was released to the containment sump.  The area was isolated and incident responders began washing down the area to the sump.  The released material and water was then pumped to a safe location.  A diaphram pump was used to pump the excess material from the tanker back to the hazardous waste storage tank.  The exterior of the tanker was washed down and the driver released to leave.  Because the material was fully contained and the contents of the wastestream were known, the release did not exceed the reportable quantity.
column169: On 12-4-2013 at 2:00 PM, an incident investigation was held.  The events of the incident were reviewed and discussed.  Based on the results of the incident investigation, the following items were determined to be the causes (direct or indirect) of this incident:   1) The material Information (data) plate was not reviewed prior to the start of loading.  Typically, a 6,000 – 7,000 gallon tanker is delivered to the site to transport waste.  On this occasion, a 4,600 gallon tanker was delivered.  If the requested tanker truck was sent, the overflow would not have occurred.    2) There is a local high level transmitter that is inserted into the tanker truck in order to alert the material handler that the tanker is reaching a high level.  In talking with all personnel present or in the area just prior to the incident, the audible alarm was not heard.  The most likely cause of the alarm not being activated is due to debris in the tank interfering with the movement of the float on the level transmitter.    3) There is a high/high level alarm that includes both visual alarms as well as action alarms.  The DCS computer screen in the tank farm control room indicated the high/high level alarm was activated.  However, the action alarm (which is intended to cutoff the transfer pump) did not work.  During a prior automation software upgrade, the action alarm was disabled on the DCS controlling module.  Therefore, there was no automatic shutoff.   This item has been corrected.

column168: 12/4/13: At 7:54pm, CR train FM21/PR21, was shoving east onto the Carteret (NJ) Industrial track off of the Chemical Coast Secondary to deliver railcars to Kinder Morgan Liquid Terminals, Carteret, N J. Crew forgot to disengage/remove the derail located at the west end of the Carteret Industrial Track, allowing the 1st two cars, head out in the shove, to derail. Tank car ACFX 72805, load Vinyl Acetate Stabilized, non-jacketed 111A100W1, the lead car in the shove, derailed and rolled onto it's left side about 45 degrees and came to rest on an old concrete base along side the track. Contact with this concrete base led to the tank shell being dented on the left side, at mid-length of the car at and near the side ladder. Dent measured approximately 4-5' in length x 2-3' in height x approximately 4" depth. The other tank car involved, DOWX 6771, load Combustible Liquid N.O.S. (Dipropylene Glycol Methyl Ether Acetate), PG III material, non-jacketed 111A100W1, 2nd car from the shoving end, derailed lead "A" end trucks but remained upright. Evacuation of nearby hotel (128 people total) was ordered by local responders only during the rerailing process. ACFX 72805 was rerailed without incident and moved to Conrail's Port Reading (NJ) Yard shop track, a distance of approximately 3 miles, after being denied entry into the original consignee, Kinder Morgan Terminals for unloading. Product to be transferred into another tank car of same commodity service, supplied by shipper, at a later date, and further cleaned/purged of residue/vapor. DOWX 6771 was rerailed without incident, repaired and was accepted into the original consignee, Kinder Morgan Terminals, for unloading.

column168: At 0845 on 12/14/13 KCS responded to a reported diesel spill in the Shreveport yard. The spill was reported to be coming from tank car AGCX 10153  located on the 30 track adjacent to Shanty road. Upon initial site arrival it was observed approximately 5-10 gallons had been released  with the majority of the product located between 30 track and Shanty road. AGCX 10153 was observed to have the manway open with no manway gasket present. Upon closer investigation it was found that the manway bracket was cracked. This deformation in the manway bracket did not allow the KCS responders to install a manway gasket to the nozzle.     The responders were able to close the manway and tighten all manway bolts tool tight. The non-complying DOT specification packaged was moved a short distance via supervised special switch, approximately 4,500 feet, per 49CFR174.50, to the waybill consigned location for unloading. AGCX arrived at the  unloading location with no further product released. AGCX 10153 has been bad ordered with the car department.    On 12/16/13 the fuel from tank car ACGX 10153 was successfully off-loaded by the KCS diesel shop into an on-site above ground diesel storage tank utilizing the fueling track and standard off-loading procedures. This tank car will be purged and cleaned of hazmat residue, placards removed, appropriately tagged and marked, and then the non-complying tank car will be transported under FRA One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) to car owners home-shop for repairs to manway hinge.    * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.      (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: At approximately 1:20 pm on December 26, 2013 loaded tank car ACFX 73470 (Sulfuric Acid, Spent) was bad ordered at the KCS Beaumont Yard. Appropriate notifications were made and emergency responders activated.     *No injuries reported.    Emergency responders arrived shortly after notification and began assessing the tank car. After assessment had concluded, the shipper (Total Petrochemicals + Refining, Port Arthur, Texas) offered this tank car with the Liquid Line valve not completely closed and the Liquid Line secondary closure plug was hand threaded. The plug took over three full turns to close plug tool tight. The Liquid Line ball valve, which was just slightly open, was turned to the proper closed position. The product was contained to the exterior of the rail car and was cleaned off with absorbent pads and wipes.     The tank car was then deemed to be repaired and therefore released back into transportation.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. column168: At 1231 EST on 12/9/13, ERTS was notified by R&L Carriers about the release, which was discovered at 1200 EST on 12/9/13. ERTS notified Qualified Spill Response (QSR), an environmental contractor, which responded to the incident. QSR discovered that the 55 gallon drum had released it's entire contents to the trailer, with some of the material leaking out of the trailer, and impacting the tractor and the asphalt below.  QSR containerized the released material, and pressure washed the interior of the trailer, the trailer, and the impacted asphalt below the trailer.  The water and removed material was then containerized for pending disposal.

column168: On December 8, 2013 at approximately 17:15 hours contractor personnel working in the CSXT Willard, OH yard discovered an odor from tank car UTLX 674927, a loaded tank car of molten sulfur.  The car was isolated and the shipper, BP Products, was notified CHEMTREC Report # 2013-12-08-00036.  Joe McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, along with SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found that six 6 of the eight 8 manway cover securement bolts were less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, Greg Crum at 630-525-0120.  The manway cover securement bolts were tightened and the car released for transport.      Cause Code:    200  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 12/18/2013 at 1231, personnel in the CSXT Avon Big Four Yard discovered GATX 57056, a loaded tank car of Sodium Sulfide Solution, leaking from the vacuum relief valve. The car was isolated and Hendricks County Communication Center and NRC #1068923 were notified.  CHEMTREC Report # 2013121800199. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief valve hissing. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Heritage Crystal CleanJoe Licari 312-898-1983. Contractor personnel fixed the problem by depressing the spring in the vacuum relief device to reset the valve. The leak was secured. This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 1028  NARRI: 2 (5+5+0)x(2+0)=40
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On December 20, 2013 at 03:15 hours, a yard crew in West Springfield Yard smelled an odor near PROX 31369, a residue tank car of LPG Propane while coupling the track. The valve was hand tightened closed and the plug wrench tightened, PROX 31369 was checked with a CGI meter, no further issues were found and the tank car was released for transport. column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 6 ounces of material had  escaped from the container. Further investigation found no gasket on the drum.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and  placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: Drivers will continue to be diligent in inspecting drums for transfer.  Generator was contacted and discussion ensued as to the condition of a drum used to transfer materials or waste.

column168: While loading a drum onto the Safety Kleen truck the shippers operator of the forklift punctured the drum with the fork of the forklift. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and over packed the leaking drum. The trailer floor and containment area was cleaned with a cleaning compound and packed into the over pack then returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility. The New Jersey DEP was notified (1312311250-00)
column169: Loading and tranfer procedures with forklift are being reviewed with the shippers operator of this incident and all facility personell.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste at Clean Harbors Laurel MD facility was being loaded with intransit drums for continued transportation to the intended waste disposal facility. While doing the transfer the fork truck driver accidently punctured the side of a 55 gallon steel drum near the top of the drum. Fork truck driver immediately removed fork truck, put down absorbant pads and spill booms inside trailer. Fork truck driver contacted supervisor,liquids not absorbed by pads and booms was captured in secondary containment and later pumped into a drum for future shipment. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and packed into the over pack then returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed by the driver. The drum was damaged due to the forklift puncturing the drum. In order to prevent a recurrence, the plant forklift operator was spoken with and is being retrained regarding the importance of safe forklift operation and preventing these type of incidences from reoccuring. Also we felt lighting was a contributing factor and the facility manager is going to install added lighting.

column168: Driver stopped at rest area and noticed small release from tanker. Approximately three (3) liquid cups of UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid 10-30% solution was released to the body of the tanker. A contractor was dispatched for cleanup activities. The released material was neutralized and absorbent pads were used. All cleanup debris was collected and containerized for disposal. Parties investigated and determined that cause of leak was cracked plate on the tank upper manway cover.  The cracked plate was replaced to prevent further release of material. During repair operations the gasket seals were replaced as a precautionary measure. No impact to soils, storm drains, waterways, human health, public, or transportation routes occurred as a result of this incident.

During a routine load and tire check, the driver noticed liquid material dripping from inside the trailer. The driver placed absorbent pads and a bucket under the dripping area and called his supervisor. A response crew was summoned. Upon arrival, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer. It was found that one drum had a crack in the body. A suitable salvage drum was used to overpack the drum and all of the absorbent material used to contain the spill. The truck was then dispatched to the intended waste  disposal facility. Local fire department was called as well as the PA DEP.
column169: Upon investigation we determined the drum failed to withstand the rigors of transportation. The generator will be billed for the cleanup costs and has instituted procedures to more closely inspect drums prior to filling.

column168: On December 2, 2013 at approximately 19:00EST a Quality Carriers CTMV was involved in a multiple vehicle incident which may have been a result of medical issues  with the driver of the truck. At the time of the incident the unit was  transporting UN1866 resin solution. The Tanker struck a school bus transporting children, there were several injuries due to the incident but none where as a direct result of the hazardous material and all were reported as minor. The Tanker unit left the road after impacting the bus and rolled over onto the adjacent ditch line and shoulder. The impact of the rollover caused the tanker unit to rupture releasing approximately ½ of the approximate 40,000 pound cargo onto the shoulder and ditch. The TCEQ dispatched a local contractor to contain and control the release to minimize impact.

column168: Driver for AJ Weigand noticed that a small amount of product was leaking from the main valve of his tanker trucker. The driver pulled into a Truck Stop of America and contained the leak with a bucket. The leak was releasing one quart of product per hour. A contractor was dispatched to help contain the leak and to perform a product transfer to a replacement tanker. The cleanup and transfer was completed within 2 hours.

A leak was discovered while this drum was sitting in a in-transit transfer area at the Clean Harbors warehouse in Tucker, GA for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. column169: Informed the generator that drums should be inspected before use and need to meet DOT requirements.  Clean Harbors Tucker office reminded the drivers to thoroughly inspect all containers for integrity prior to them being placed into the transport vehicles.

column168: The driver was conducting a routine load check of his trailer while in transit and he detected a foul odor smell.  The driver immediately notified his dispatcher.  The driver was not aware if any containers shifted.  The spill seem to be centralized in the middle of the trailer, so it could not be determined what type of material and how much material was released.  When Clean Harbors hazmat team arrived, donning appropriate Personsonal Protective Equipment (PPE), made entry into the trailer and initiated moving containers in order to identify the leaking container.  It was determined that a 16 gallon drum was loaded on top of the 5 gallon container causing it to crush resulting it to puncture and leak the Corrosive liquid onto the trailer floor.  The hazmat team absorb the material off the deck of trailer and placed both the 5 gallon container and absorbent material into a salvage drum for disposal and relased for transportation to intended disposal facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the location that offered the shipment for transportation have been instructed to place the smaller containers on top of larger containers when loading vehicles for transport.

column168: Tank car TILX 200043 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area during movement in the railyard and TILX 200043 was isolated in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting TILX 200043 reported finding the liquid eduction line's closure (blind) flange's bolt nuts loose with one nut not applied. column168: Tank car GATX 200886 was reported leaking commodity from its manway closure in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected GATX 200886 and reported finding all six manway securement bolts tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket condition revealed the applied gasket was dried/hardened and not sealing properly. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly resecured. Intact manway cover shipper seal VDTC 013569 was replaced by seal BNSF 096014. A small amount of spillage near the manway nozzle evaporated. No further commodity release was observed during subsequent movement in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Safety Inspector in the railyard observed tank car TILX 192663 dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve's (BOV) closure cap (BOC). The BOV operating handle was not pinned in its closed position due to the non-functioning worn/damaged retaining pin, thus allowing the unpinned operating handle to move downward to a partially open position. With the assistance of a nearby BNSF employee, the BOV operating handle was immediately moved to the closed position and pinned using a FRA Inspection seal stopping the commodity release at the BOC connection. Ground spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: WHILE LOADING UPS DELIVERY VEHICLES IN THE UPS NASSAU, NY FACILITY, EMPLOYEES IDENTIFIED A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE (LABELED CORROSIVE AND OXIDIZER) AT 04:47 HRS AND CALLED  IN A UPS DESIGNATED RESPONDER TO ADDRESS THE SPILL.  AT 05:24, THE LEAKING PACKAGE BEGAN TO SMOKE (FIRST RED, THEN WHITE SMOKE) AND A DECISION WAS MADE TO EVACUATE THE FACILITY, WHILE A CONTRACT OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS CALLED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ALSO CALLED WHEN THE PACKAGE IGNITED AT APPX 06:30 HRS.  WHILE THE PACKAGE WAS EXTINGUISHED SOON THEREAFTER, THE FACILITY REMAINED EVACUATED DUE TO SMOKE WITHIN THE BUILDING.  THREE UPS EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN FOR OUTPATIENT TREATMENT OF SMOKE INHALATION.  WHILE NO PHYSICAL EVIDENCE OF THE INCIDENT PACKAGE REMAINS, DISCUSSION WITH EMPLOYEES LED TO SUSPICIONS THAT THE PACKAGE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT WAS ONE PART OF A TWO-PIECE SHIPMENT FROM AVANTOR.  A SECOND, INTACT NITRIC ACID PACKAGE WAS FOUND IN THE FACILITY AND RECORDS SHOWED THAT IT WAS ASSOCIATED WITH THE PACKAGE SUSPECTED TO BE INVOLVED IN THE FIRE.  WHILE NO OTHER PACKAGES WERE DAMAGED BY THE FIRE, SOME CONVEYOR EQUIPMENT AND OTHER UPS PROPERTY WERE DAMAGED IN THE INCIDENT. GREAT CARE WAS TAKEN TO ESTABLISH THE SUITABLE AIR QUALITY WITHIN THE FACILITY BEFORE EMPLOYEES RE-ENTERED THE BUILDING.
column169: PACKAGING REGULATIONS FOR NITRIC ACID NEED TO BE IMPROVED.  BY PETITION DATED SEPTEMBER 5, 2012, UPS HAS ALREADY URGED PHMSA TO STRENGTHEN PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS FOR NITRIC ACID (P-1601).

column168: At 0139 EST on 12/27/13, R&L Carriers personnel discovered leaking batteries in a trailer.  They were moved from the trailer to the concrete dock.  ERTS was notified at 0145 EST on 12/27/13.  ERTS dispatched USES to respond to the site for clean-up.  USES personnel estimated that a total of 6 gallons of battery acid was released from two batteries.  Neutralizing material was applied to the impacted areas of the trailer floor and concrete dock.  The neutralizing material was then containerized for disposal, and the batteries were staged on a pallet and wrapped in poly sheeting for disposition determination by R&L Carriers.

During unloading of a trailer, a box containing jugs of Hypochlorite solution was found to be leaking.  A HazMat contractor was called to the site to clean up the spill.  They utilized absorbents to recover the released product and placed into a container for disposal.

column168: ON 12-02-2013 AT 0735 HRS CDT, I WAS ADVISED BY TRAINMASTER, DUNN, OF A TANK CAR OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP. TRAINMASTER DUNN ADVISED THAT CAR # UTLX 21151 WAS PLACED IN ISOLATION ON THE "OLD RIP TRACK" #5 DO TO THE FLAMMABILITY OF ETHANOL UN 1987. I SUBSEQUENTLY ARRIVED AT INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD, BLUE ISLAND YARD, AT RIVERDALE, ILLINOIS AND SUBSEQUENTLY EXAMINED CAR AND NOTED THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) CONTAINED PRODUCT ON THE PRD CAP. ADDITIONALLY I NOTED THAT THE ROD IN CENTER OF CAP WAS LOOSE (PIC 2 OF 4). I SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACTED HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, "SUNPRO SERVICES" TO REPOND TO YARD IN ATTEMPT TO REMEDIATE THE PRD. UPON ARRIVAL OF DAVE ESTEP, "SUNPRO" WE ATTEMPT TO RESEAT THE PRD CAP AND GASKET ON UPON REMOVAL NOTED THAT THE INTERNAL COMPONENTS OF THE PRD WERE MISSING AND PRESUMED TO BE INSIDE THE CAR FILLED WITH PRODUCT. (PICS 3-4 & 4-4). WE SUBSEQUENTLY PLACED THE PRD BACK ON THE CAR AND I NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, ADM, MR. JOHN MARTIN. MR. MARTIN ADVICED THAT A NEW PRD WOULD BE SHIPPED TO "SUNPRO" FOR INSTALLATION AND MOVEMENT APPROVAL WOULD BE OBTAINED TO RETURN CAR. ON 12.20.2013 A NEW PRD WAS RECIEVED AND INSTALLED ON CAR BY "SUNPRO SERVICES." CAR IS CURRENTLY ON HOLD PENDING FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL.
column169: ON 12-03-2013, I WAS INSTRUCTED VERBALLY AND VIA EMAIL FROM FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION (FRA) HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTOR, MICHAEL BENNETT THAT UPON REPAIR OF THE CAR WITH A NEW PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) TO SEND THE DEFECTIVE PRD TO THE FRA FOR EXAMINATION. ADDITIONALLY MR. MARTIN FROM ADM WAS ALSO COPIED ON THE EMAIL AND WAS ADVISED TO RETURN TO ME THE COMPONENTS OF THE PRD FROM THE INTERIOR OF THE CAR SO ALL OF THE DEVICE CAN BE FORWARDED FOR EXAMINATION.

column168: Tank car TILX 198702 while in the railyard was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). Contract responders transferred all commodity from TILX 198702 to another suitable tank car by 1800 hrs. CST, 12/31/2013 without further incident. Afterwards, dripping at TILX 198702's BOV ceased and all spillage evaporated.

column168: Tank car TILX 315716 was reported leaking commodity from its manway closure while in the railyard. TILX 315716 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting TILX 315716 reported finding manway securement bolts/nuts not tool tight. A portion of the applied manway gasket was hanging down from the manway closure. Further inspection of the applied manway gasket revealed it was deteriorated (cut and shredded), therefore not providing the required closure seal. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway closure was properly secured. Observed spillage around TILX 315716's manway nozzle and on its side shell was wiped, then water rinsed with all rinsate captured and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  Intact shipper seal Gallup Refinery 9026 at the manway was replaced by seal numbered 00086587. All other valves and fittings were found secure.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

We plug our transfer pumps into a reel that can be rolled up with the extension cord on it and plugged into the customers outlet.  Once the operator had completed filling the Hydrochloric Acid tank, he unplugged the extension cord from the customers outlet and unhooked the hose from the transfer pump and the tank and put it away.  He failed to unhook the acid transfer pump power cord from the reel.  He then proceeded to plug the extension cord back into the customers outlet so that I could pump the next product.  The customers outlet was directly next to the tanks where the product is located.  after observing that the product was going into the customers tank with no leaks (25 to 30 seconds) he proceeded to walk to the truck to check the connection.  He noticed Hydrochloric acid dripping from the bottom of the box truck. He unplugged the extension cord from the outlet and went to the truck to assess the damage.  The Hydrochloric Acid transfer pump had energized and pumped material into the back of the truck.    The employee began using a garden hose to wash the truck, but discontinued due to low pressure. He notificed the customer, and a decision was made to notify the locadl fire department. They arrived within 2-5 minutes of the phone call.  When the Fire Department arrived they flushed the acid down the storm drain and flushed the area with water for about 30 minutes.  They also sprayed out the back of the truck and underneath the body of the truck as well.  Contact information to the Avon Fire Department was shared, and well as the BOL.
column169: Procedure has been modified and updated through out the company to prevent a repeat. Incident has been reviewed by senior management.

The released ink impacted the concrete dock, but did not impact any soils, drains or waterways.  ERTS was notified of the release at 1318 EST. The absorbents were then containerized for disposal.

column168: On December 30, 2013, at 1228 EST, ERTS was notified by Landstar Ranger that a shipment of UN3145 Alkylphenols, liquid, was being delivered in one of their trailers to T&T Forwarding in Laredo, TX, when it was discovered that one of the drums had a puncture hole in the side.  The hole was approximately 3 inches wide by 1 inch high.  The cause of the puncture is unknown, but is presumed to be caused by impact with a forklift. Approximately 15 gallons of material was released from the drum, and impacted the interior of the trailer, but did not impact anything outside of the trailer.     Upon notification, ERTS contacted United States Environmental Services (USES).  Once USES personnel arrived on-scene  at approximately 1430 EST.  They overpacked the damaged drum, and applied absorbents to the released material.  The overpacked drum, along with the rest of the shipment, was accepted by T&T Forwarding.
While loading Conway employee dropped freight.  One was recouped and the other was damage and put into a recovery drum.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED FROM BACK OF TRAILER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO SIDE OF THE ROAD, ISOLATED AREA, AND COORDINATED RESPONSE EFFORTS. EP&S OF VT OF STONE MOUNTAIN, GEORGIA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON ARRIVAL ON SITE, FREE PRODUCT WAS DETECTED WITHIN SOILS BENEATH TRAILER, WHERE TRUCK CAME TO REST. TRAILER WAS INSPECTED, AND ONE (1) 275-GALLON TOTE WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT HAD RELEASED TO TRAILER FLOOR AND IMMEDIATE SOILS. EP&S OF VT NEUTRALIZED THE FREE PRODUCT ON TRAILER FLOOR, PUMPED THE REMAINING FREE PRODUCT FROM DAMAGED TOTE INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, AND WIPED CONTAMINATED FREIGHT. SITE WAS SECURED, PENDING RETURN DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS FOR COMPLETION OF EXCAVATION. EP&S OF VT RETURNED THE FOLLOWING DAY, EXCAVATED IMPACTED SOILS, AND RESTORED SITE TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. APPROXIMATELY 3 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE RECOVERED, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: Train 194U126 went into emergency in Vivian, WV, derailing 16 cars, 12 of which were Elevated Temperature Material (asphalt) cars.  Five were only wheels off which were repaired and forwarded to destination.  Two tank cars GATX 213134 and UTLX 67591 lost thery entire load and UTLX 644254 lost part of it's load into a ditch and into the Elkhorn River.  All losses were due to head puntures and tears in the head.  Other cars derailed were GATX 63818 (wheels only), UTLX 662478 (wheels only), SHPX 209866 (wheels only), UTLX 643807 (wheels only), UTLX 661813 (wheels only).  GATX 213111 rolled 90 deg. no leak. GATX 213081, rolled 30 deg. jacket damage only.  UTLX 662158 rolled 90 deg. leaking from manway and vac. relief device.  UTLX 649450 upright with large dent in side, leak from the vac. relief device.  GATX 213134 rolled 180 deg. with B end in river, hole in the top of the head, lost about 1/3 load.  UTLX 67591 rolled 90 deg. crack or hole in B end head. lost entire load.  UTLX 644254 upright with hole or crack in head, lost entire load.  NS Derailment Number D-108317.  It is estimated that approximately 40,000 gallons of product was lost.  Please note all costs are preliminary as not all invoices have been received nor has work been completed (product transfers).
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A LEAKING HAZMAT WAS CALLED IN AT 1415 BY DAN MARTEL IN UNLOAD BAY 40. THE FIBERBOARD PACKAGE WAS ON ITS SIDE CRUSHED OPEN AND CONTENTS WERE COMING OUT. THE FIBERBOARD PACKAGE CONTAINED 2 1-POUND PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF SMOKELESS POWDER FOR SMALL ARMS. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO CRACKS ON THE BOTTLES. I FOLLOWED MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO PSC FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: Pressure from a fork lift tong caused the body of a 55-gallon drum of UN1263 to release approximately one gallon of material to the pallet and the trailer floor. Facility personnel tipped the drum on its side to prevent further release. No impact to soils, storm drains, or waterways occurred. A contractor was dispatched to remove impact from the release. Absorbent pads were used to wipe down the side of the drum and the impacted pallet was broken down and containerized in a 55 gallon drum. Granular absorbents were used to collect the released material on the trailer floor and was combined with the rest of the cleanup debris for disposal.

column168: Driver was switching to unload another product and moved the truck. In the process of moving the truck the driver hooked the hose to the trailer but forgot to hook the fitting to the underground storage tank.  Driver pulled discharge handle and spilled aprox; 25-50 gallons of gas onto the store parking lot. Driver was able to contain most of the spill but some of the product reached a storm drain. HAZ mat and response contractor came onsite and cleaned up the spill.  They also were able to clean out the storm drain and remove all contaminated debris. Speedi Dri was used on the parking lot to cleanup remainder of the spill.

column168: A westbound BNSF unit grain train operating on main track 1 derailed in front of an approaching eastbound BNSF unit petroleum crude oil train operating on main track 2. A derailed rail car from the grain train fouled main track 2 which was struck by the lead locomotive of the oil train, resulting in the subsequent derailment of both lead locomotives and the head 20 rail cars of the oil train. column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT KROGER #345 IN SOMERSET, KY FOR GAS/DIESEL DELIVERY. VAPOR RECOVERY WAS HOOKED UP FOR ALL COMPARTMENTS. 800 GALLONS OF ULSD WAS DROPPED FIRST, #2 COMPARTMENT; AT SAME TIME 3500 GALLONS OF REGULAR GASOLINE WAS SUPPOSED TO BE DROPPING FROM #4 COMPARTMENT. DRIVER TOOK HOSE FROM #2 COMPARTMENT AND HOOKED TO #1 COMPARTMENT, 3100 GALLONS REGULAR GASOLINE AND DROPPED. DRIVER THOUGHT THAT COMPARTMENT #4 HAD EMPTIED SO HE DRAINED THE HOSE AND HOOKED TO #3 COMPARTMENT, 1400 GALLONS REGULAR GASOLINE. NO PRODUCT HAD DROPPED FROM #4 OR #3. DRIVER SAW PRODUCT IN HIS FITTING SIGHT GLASS AT THE TRAILER END, HE OPENED AND CLOSED THE SHUT OFF VALVE A COUPLE OF TIMES AND THE PRODUCT STAYED IN THE HOSE; HE THOUGHT THE PRESSURE NEEDED TO BE RELEASED SO THE PRODUCT WOULD BE ABLE TO DRAIN OUT OF HIS HOSE. HE FAILED TO SHUT THE VALVE OFF AND WHEN HE RAISED THE FITTING, PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPILL OUT. HE WAS ABLE TO GET THE FITTING REATTACHED, HOWEVER, THE RUBBER GASKET HAD COME OUT OF THE FITTING AND PRODUCT WAS STILL RUNNING OUT OF THE DROP. HE GOT SPILL PADS TO KEEP PRODUCT FROM GOING INTO THE DRAIN AND WAS ABLE TO STOP PRODUCT FROM GETTING INTO ONE DRAIN, HOWEVER, THERE WAS ANOTHER DRAIN UNDER A PARKED CAR THAT HE DID NOT SEE. HE THEN REALIZED THAT HE HAD NOT SHUT OFF PRODUCT FLOW AND IMMEDIATELY DONE SO AT THE COMPARTMENT VALVE. PRODUCT FLOW STOPPED AT THIS POINT. HAD HE NOT GOTTEN EXCITED, HE WOULD HAVE SHUT OFF THE VALVE FIRST, THEN CHECKED THE LINE. SOMERSET PULASKI CO. S.R.T., SOMERSET FIRE DEPARTMENT, STATE FIRE MARSHALL, STATE ERT AND SOUTHERN SERVICES RESPONDED TO SCENE FOR INVESTIGATION AND CLEAN UP. LATER DISCOVERED THAT THE FLAPPER ON THE DROP-TUBE SHUTOFF VALVE IN THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK HAD MALFUNCTIONED.
column169: The tank trailer and hoses used to off load the product did not malfunction in any way. Driver error caused the spill. The driver should have closed the shut off valve before "burping" the hose to relieve pressure. The driver was unaware that the product had not dropped. It was later discovered that the Flapper on the Drop-tube shutoff valve in the underground storage tank had malfunctioned and did not allow any product to be unloaded. We have been addressing these types of incidents in our training sessions. Making drivers aware of different situations that can happen hopefully helps them to understand what to do and what not to do.

column168: ON DECEMBER 26, 2013 A M-I SWACO DELIVERY TRUCK LOADED WITH SEVEN STAINLESS STEEL INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS FILLED WITH HYDROGEN SULFIDE SCAVENGER WAS EN ROUTE TO A CUSTOMER LOCATION. WHILE TRAVELING DOWN TX HWY. 85 near dilley, TX, A TWO LANE PAVED ROAD, THE DRIVER DROPPED THE RIGHT SIDE WHEELS OFF OF THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. THE TRAVEL SPEED WAS APPROXIMATELY 65 MPH WITH A POSTED SPEED LIMIT OF 70 MPH. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STEER THE TRUCK BACK ON THE ROADWAY, OVER CORRECTING, AND LOST CONTROL. THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER TWICE BEFORE COMING TO A STOP ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. ALL SEVEN OF THE IBCs, WHICH WERE SECURED BY FOUR INCH STRAPS, BROKE LOOSE AND DEPARTED THE VEHICLE. TWO OF THE IBCs LEAKED 193 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. DUE TO THE SPILL THE HIGHWAY WAS SHUT DOWN BY TX DPS FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PERFORMED THE CLEANUP ON DECEMBER 26TH AND DECEMBER 27TH. AS A RESULT OF THE CLEANUP, TWO LARGE ROLL-OFF BOXES UNCONTAMINATED SOIL. column168: Our driver took a Cymetech prepped tank over to Cymetech to load. Cymetech did their pressure testing of the tankbefore loading twice as they always do. After Cymetech hadloaded about 12,000 Ibs. they shut down loading. The loader stated that 2 drops of product had appeared where theexternal valve pipe connects to the bonnet. Product has a high freeze point and had frozen. They off loaded theproduct and asked for another tank. The next tank was loaded without incident. No product hit the ground and noproduct was lost. We had the trailer cleaned and re-tested the valves, and they passed all the tests.

Immediately after the gasket broke the driver closed the inlet valve to the customer storage tank and reversed the pump to clear the lines and pump back into the tank truck. Once lines and pump where cleared the internal and external valves on the tank truck were shut to contain remaining material. Driver notified direct supervisor of the incident and customer was also notified. Driver was dispatched back to facility as product could not be offloaded safely. Third party emergency response crew was dispatched to customer location to remove contaminated soil.
column169: In reviewing this incident a more detailed PM program is being established for the tractor pumps so that the interior parts that cannot be seen during a visual inspection are insepcted on a routine basis. Tractor pumps will be PM'd on a quarterly basis unless any visual issues are identified then the pump will be put out of service until maintenance is performed.

column169: WHEN USING THE TANKERS TO PUMP OUT PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, THE TOP SENSORS ON EACH COMPARTMENT DO NOT STOP LOADING WHEN CAPACITY IS REACHED. DOME LIDS ARE OPEN BECAUSE VISUAL GAGING IS THE ONLY MEANS CURRENTLY USED TO VERIFY THE LOAD. DEVELOPMENT OF AN OVERFILL SENSOR CONNECTED TO THE PTO SHUTOFF WOULD HELP PREVENT SPILLS LIKE THIS. OBVIOUSLY ADDED PEOPLE, HELP AND EXPERIENCE IS A PLUS WHEN PUMPING OUT A TANK, BUT IN THIS CASE IT WAS NOT ENOUGH.

column168: Our vehicle was struck from behind by another carrier's tractor trailer rig. No hazardous conditions were created or existed while performing this process.

column14: N. BOUND LANE OF I-35 BETWEEN
column168: The release of an estimated 4000 gallons of diesel fuel occurred on December 7, 2013, when a semi-truckwas driving in the north bound lane of Interstate I-35 towards Emporia, Kansas. It swerved off the Turnpikeand overturned in a drainage ditch of a grassy shoulder along the east side of the I-35. The Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE) was notified. KDHE notified the Local EmergencyManager who sent the local fire department to the site. To prevent the flow of fuel toward Jacobs Creek(approx 1/4 mile south), the fire dept. constructed a berm along the south end of ditch. A private Emergency Response Contractor arrived at the site on December 7, 2013. They observed that the majority of the fuel had already seeped into the soil. On December 7, 2013, the Contractor dug potholes(12 to 24 inches deep) across the ditch to recover free product. No product was recovered. FromDecember 12 to 13, 2013, the impacted soils were excavated from the site and transported to the Coffee County Landfill in Burlington, Kansas, for disposal; the excavation was backfilled beginning on December16, 2013, and was completed on December 18, 2013. The KDHE was on site during the initial portion ofthe soil excavation. Following the excavation, a field device (flame ionization detector) indicated very lowto non-detect concentrations of diesel fuel in the soil. The backfill and reseeding of the area werecompleted to the satisfaction of the Kansas Turnpike Authority.

column168: V1 IS A WHITE 2011 DODGE FLATBED TRUCK TOWING A BLACK 2012 PJ GOOSENECK FLATBED TRAILER  V2 IS A MAROON 2006 KENWORTH TRUCK TRACTOR TOWING A SILVER 2013 STEPHENS TANKER TRAILER    V1 WAS EN ROUTE FROM VAN HOOK ND TO NEWTOWN ND AT APPROXIMATELY 45 MILES PER HOUR SOUTHBOUND ON ND 8. THE DRIVER OF V1 REPORTED THAT HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION AND ATTEMPTED TO STOP. THE DRIVER OF V1 REPORTED BEING UNABLE TO STOP AND STRUCK V2 MIDWAY THROUGH THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER OF V1 WAS TRAPPED INSIDE VEHICLE ONE, AND HAD TO BE EXTRICATED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. IN ORDER FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO SUCCESSFULLY GET TO THE DRIVER OF V1, V1 HAD TO BE PULLED AWAY FROM V2 AS IT WAS LEAKING CRUDE OIL. V1 CAME TO REST FACING SOUTHWEST ALONG SIDE OF V2'S TRAILER.  THE DRIVER OF V1 WAS WEARING HIS SEATBELT AND NO AIR BAGS DEPLOYED. THE DRIVER OF V1 HAD A LACERATION TO HIS HEAD AND A LEG INJURY. THE DRIVER OF V1 WAS TRANSPORTED TO TRINITY HOSPITAL IN MINOT ND BY PARSHALL AMBULANCE. V1 AND ITS TRAILER WERE TOWED BY OLSON'S TOWING OUT OF MINOT TO A PRIVATE WORK YARD NORTH OF THE CRASH SCENE.  V2 WAS EN ROUTE FROM NEWTOWN ND TO TIOGA ND NEGOTIATING A LEFT TURN FROM NORTH DAKOTA HIGHWAY 23 (EASTBOUND) TO NORTH DAKOTA HIGHWAY 8 (NORTHBOUND) AT APPROXIMATELY 10 MILES PER HOUR. THE DRIVER OF V2 REPORTED SEEING V1 SOUTHBOUND ON HIGHWAY 8, BUT ASSUMED THAT V1 WAS GOING TO BE ABLE TO STOP. THE DRIVER OF V2 DID NOT REPORT SEEING V1 AGAIN UNTIL HE WAS STRUCK BY V1. THE DRIVER OF V2 REPORTED GETTING OUT OF HIS VEHICLE AND SURVEYING THE DAMAGE. THE DRIVER OF V2 THEN ASKED BYSTANDERS TO CALL 911 AND THEN HE CHECKED ON THE DRIVER OF V1. THE DRIVER OF V2 REPORTED NOT BEING ABLE TO GET THE DRIVER OF V1 OUT OF THE WRECKAGE. THE DRIVER OF V2 WAS NOT INJURED, AND REPORTED WEARING HIS SEATBELT. V2 DID NOT HAVE AIRBAGS, AND DID NOT REQUIRE A TOW. V2 HAD BEEN TRANSPORTING 233.52 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL. ALL 233.52 BARRELS LEAKED INTO THE SOUTHWEST AND NORTHWEST DITCHES OF ND 23 AND ND 8.  CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED BY STRATA.    CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF THE CRASH WERE DUSK AT A SLIGHTLY LIGHTED INTERSECTION.  THERE IS LIGHTING ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE INTERSECTION. A 1/4 INCH COAT OF ICE COVERED THE SOUTHBOUND LANE OF HIGHWAY 8 AT THE INTERSECTION. THERE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE ICY CONDITIONS ON ND 23. THE SPEED LIMIT ON ND 8 IS 65 MILES PER HOUR, AND ON ND 23 ARE 55 MILES PER HOUR. WIND SPEEDS WERE SUSTAINED AT APPROXIMATELY 12 MILES PER HOUR FROM THE NORTHWEST. THE TEMPERATURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 10 DEGREES FARENHEIT. TROOPER WARE TOOK PHOTOS OF THE CRASH SCENE. INITIAL CLEAN UP OF THE CRUDE OIL TOOK APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS.

column168: • Driver had been contracted since September 2013 with no incidents, accidents or roadside inspections reported during this time.  • Driver started his shift at 5 am (regular start time) after being off duty for 11 hours. Driver worked 12.5 hours the prior day, and was off the previous 3 days.  • This has been his regular shift and work schedule since he contracted with Gibson as an Owner Operator.   • Driver states he conducted complete pre-trip inspection with nothing to report as deficient.  • Driver was loaded (on his 2nd load for this shift) from Flag Ranch to unload at Midland Station which is the approved and designated route for this delivery.  • Driver was eastbound in the right lane on State Loop 250 in Midland approaching the intersection of CR 1150.  • Other driver/vehicle was northbound on CR 1150 which is controlled with a stop sign.  • Speed data reports support driver statement of approximately 45-50 mph with a posted speed of 55 mph prior to the incident.  • Road conditions were dry and clear, weather conditions were clear and sunny.   • OV disregarded stop sign and drove in front of IV resulting in a collision.   • IV swerved to the left prior to impact causing the unit to leave the road way at speed, lost control, the tractor 5th wheel plate bolts sheared and the trailer disconnected from the tractor and rolled over. The tractor did not roll.  • Approximately 5 gallons was released and contained for cleanup and disposal by Talon.  • Other driver was cited by DPS for failure to ‘yield right of way’.
column169: • Publish PN alert warning concerning intersection hazards.  • Use as a talking point at subsequent safety meetings.

column168: On December 20, 2013 while unloading baggage from the aircraft in Baltimore, a strong odor was noted in the aircraft cabin.  Upon further investigation, a cardboard box with a leaking substance was discovered in the cargo bin.  All of the leaking liquid was absorbed into the cardboard box and there was no pooling of liquid in the cargo bin.  The Fire Department was called out to investigate and the passengers and crew de-boarded the aircraft.  The aircraft was taken out of service and another aircraft was used for the continuation of the flight.      The leaking box contained four unmarked plastic containers that held the material.  The Customer was able to provide the generic names of the materials, but the manufacturer name was not provided.  MSDS’s for the same materials from a manufacturer were located, however, the specific manufacturer of the leaking substance is unknown.  These are the names of the substances contained in the box:    Amalgambond Activator- UN2582  Amalgambond HPA Powder  Amalgabond Base- UN1247  Amalgambond Catalyst- UN1993    The three flight attendants were removed from their trip and went to the medical clinic to be checked out because of the exposure to the odor.

column168: On December 20, 2013 at approximately 1300 the TSA discovered a leaking container of Weber Odorless Turpenoid inside the passengers checked bag and removed it.  The container was inside a plastic bag and there was a light coating of the substance on the inside of the bag from the container which was causing the bag to begin to disintegrate.  There was no pooling of the substance in the bag and it appeared that none of the substance leaked into the the passengers luggage.  The cap on the container was in place and no damage was noticed on the container.

column168: 8:40AM IT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION WE HAD WHAT LOOKED LIKE A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE ON TOP BELT. DENNIS ROBINSON DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE WHILE HELPING SORT TOP BELT. I RESPONDED TO THIS PACKAGE WEARING MY PPE AND USING THE SPILL CART. I TOOK THIS PACKAGE BACK TO THE PROCESSING AREA WHERE I DISCOVEED THE CONTENTS OF THE HAZMAT PACKAGE HAD AT SOME POINT SPILLED PROBABLY FROM FREEZING AND BURSTING THE GLASS BOTTLE INSIDE THE BOX. I BROUGHT THIS FACT TO THE ATTENTION OF RM PRUSTY HUDSON.
